ndyvanguard.org/midterm-elections-2014-democrats-deja-vu-all-over-again/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:10:"Len Farber";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5331:"<div class="pf-content"><p>I have always admired clergy with a congregation who have to come up with original (or original sounding) sermons on a weekly basis. Often times the same scriptural material is being covered, but the sermon has to seek fresh meaning.</p>
<p>I admire that ability, but I don’t think I possess it. Let me be blunt. For those who have read my previous posts on the Democratic Party, this will sound like a broken record (Hmm, I wonder if this idiom will outlive vinyl recordings).</p>
<p>Democrats, get a spine!! For every Alison Lundergan Grimes who tried to run as a non-Democrat Democrat, there was an Alison Lundergan Grimes, losing candidate (feel free to call me on exceptions, but if they exist, they are just exceptions). Now to be honest, saying “Hi! I love guns and religion, hate big government and abortion, and I’m a Democrat” can work (Senator Donnelly), but more often it fails (Non-Senator Ellsworth). To their credit, both Brad Ellsworth and Joe Donnelly strike me as honest, sincere and genuine. Sadly, I cannot say that about every Democrat whose campaign was based on running away from their party and their President.</p>
<p>Get real Democrats! Your issues are the ones that matter to people. Our economy has greatly improved in contrast to Europe where they followed the prescription espoused by the Republican Party in this country. People understand that, perhaps not in those words, but they believe that spending money on infrastructure will both improve their daily lives and improve the economy, supplying jobs that cannot be outsourced.</p>
<p>In ballot measure after ballot measure the American voters have responded positively to proposals for increases in the minimum wage. Why can’t Democrats run on one of their most popular ideas? If they had a spine, they would have said, &#8220;We brought the country back from the brink and stopped the bleeding, in spite of Republican obstruction. But we know that the job isn&#8217;t complete. We still need to heal the wounds inflicted on too many Americans by this Recession. Let us finish the job task with jobs for rebuilding our infrastructure. Let’s increases in the minimum wage so that honest, hard work can provide not only pride in accomplishment, but true financial self-sufficiency as well&#8221;.</p>
<p>The economy isn&#8217;t the only issue where the people have been seen to favor the Democratic positions. Additional ballot measures included the defeat of several ‘peoplehood’ amendments, the defeat of several anti-labor measures and some pro-environment measures including a fracking ban in Denton, Texas.</p>
<p>In recent years, Democrats have captured the White House twice and subsequently lost Congress. Both Presidents Clinton and Obama listened to pundits who told them they had to “move Right and govern from the center,” except that they moved to the right of center on the Political Kelvin scale. (In physics, the Kelvin temperature scale sets zero as “absolute zero”, the lowest it is possible to go; in the Political Kelvin scale, the center is the ideological center and not movable subject to the whims or framing predilections of some Right Wing pundit.)  Democratic congressional and gubernatorial candidates haven’t fared much better when they tried to move to the Right. The Democratic Party had a proud heritage of helping the “common” American with pro-worker attitudes and belief in the social safety net. LBJ expanded that tradition, even losing the Dixiecrat wing of the party by pushing for civil rights and voting rights.</p>
<p>Since the election of Ronald Reagan, Democrats have been falling all over each other to scream “I’m not one of them! I hate Liberals! I spit on them! I’m from the ‘center,’ wherever the pundits have decided it is.” Voters haven’t been impressed.  While the Democrats have still supported several somewhat progressive ideas, they have tended to downplay that side of their agenda.</p>
<p>If the Republicans need to become the second, thoughtful, civil political party, the Democrats need to become the thoughtful, authentic first political party (sorry if I show some preferences here). If we look at the changes this country has undergone since stating that there are some individual rights which are inalienable and adopting a Bill of Rights, we see the ending of slavery, the beginning of conservation, trust-busting, the social safety net in increasing measures, increasing suffrage to a larger number of citizens and ensuring equal rights under the law. All of these ideas were different, even “liberal” in their day (yes, I know that some of those great ideas came from Republicans – then). Democrats have to remember their past and look to the future instead of running to the perceived safety of some mythical ‘center.’</p>
<p>OK, Democrats, I am saying it again. Remember who you are and proudly claim that heritage. Propose bold ideas for the future and let the voters know why you are right and why it matters. If you continue to let the Republicans define you and continue to run away from what the party used to stand for, we are doomed to grid-lock and regression. Government by a corporate oligarchy of multinationals is not a future I want to see.</p>
<p>Wake up and get a spine!</p>
