f Congress. Clearly, despite low voter turnout and a somewhat confused electorate (they voted like Democrats for ballot initiatives and like Republicans for elected officials), the Republicans are going to continue to claim &#8230; <a href="http://indyvanguard.org/what-hath-the-mid-terms-wrought-potential-scenarios-of-republican-behavior/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:10:"Len Farber";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5329:"<div class="pf-content"><p>Returning to my discussion of the mid-term elections, I have been musing on what the Republicans might do now that they have control of the both houses of Congress. Clearly, despite low voter turnout and a somewhat confused electorate (they voted like Democrats for ballot initiatives and like Republicans for elected officials), the Republicans are going to continue to claim a clear mandate for – well, for whatever non-stated agenda they believe they were elected to pursue. Exactly what course they will take is unclear.</p>
<p>If the most extreme views prevail, we can expect to see continued attacks on government in general, and President Obama in particular. This could include a continuing series of “serious investigations” into the “egregious wrongdoings” of anyone and everyone that Darrell Issa disagrees with on policy. Lawsuits against President Obama for unspecified wrongdoing or impeachment proceeding may be in the offing as well, and of course, don’t expect the Senate to use their Advise and Consent powers to ‘consent’ to anyone the President wants to appoint.</p>
<p>More troublesome, the Congress may use their purse-strings to eliminate government functions that they find troublesome, like rules and regulations that apply to the rich and powerful. Funding for the EPA? Not in the budget. Consumer protection? Not in the budget. And you can also forget about funding for education, the IRS and any enforcement of Civil Rights or Voting Rights laws. There may also be provisions inserted into legislation specifically prohibiting the executive branch from using the funding for non-Republican purposes, like measuring pollution or perhaps directing the IRS to only investigate tax returns for those earning less than $1 million dollars a year.</p>
<p>We should also note that since the President still has veto power, the option to shut down the government completely is always an option. In their view, no government services are actually needed and government workers are lazy takers who shouldn’t get paid, so it seems quite reasonable. Also, we might expect this Congress to refuse to vote to raise the debt ceiling should the need arise. Austerity, so effective in creating continued recession in Europe, is the Republican panacea (along with privatization), so it is possible that they could cripple the economy in their short stay in control of the Senate.</p>
<p>It is also possible that more ‘moderate’ Republicans (those who don’t believe that Barry Goldwater was a left-wing, communist) will forge a coalition to make compromises with the much-hated demon-President. In the past, I would have bet that President Obama would have “given away the farm” to prove that he is a bipartisan kind of guy, but these days I am not so certain. How and where he might be able to compromise will be an interesting area to watch.</p>
<p>Another possibility is complete Republican grid-lock. The more reactionary wing may get into a fight with the more ‘establishment’ Republicans and they may not even be able to agree on much legislation, preferring attacks on the President to actually passing legislation.</p>
<p>Of course, the Republicans could actually try to govern and propose reasonable, if conservative, legislation that might benefit the American people. Right.</p>
<p>At this point, I am not so optimistic. With so many potential presidential candidates looking towards 2016, we may see a complete hardening of positions within the new Congress. This is troubling. There are some differences between the consequences of Democratic positions and the consequences of Republican ones. If President Carter installed solar panels on the White House roof (a communist plot if I’ve ever heard of one), President Reagan could save America by having them removed. If Republicans succeed in giving a green light to unfettered fracking, drilling and polluting—I am sorry, but “all of the king’s horses and all of the king’s men” will not be able to put it back together again.</p>
<p>I remember back to 1987 or so, when Washington Post columnist David Broder noted the effects of one of President Reagan’s policies. After beginning his first term, while defunding intramural research at the National Institute of Mental Health (research done in government labs) and destroying the Air Traffic Controller’s union, he also quietly eliminated many people in the IRS office that investigated tax fraud. Broder noted that billions of dollars in lost taxes and penalties were being forever lost by that decision.</p>
<p>It remains to be seen what the new Republican Congress will do, how much damage it will cause and how much of it will be permanent. Only time will tell.</p>
<p>As I finish this post, the President is preparing to give a national address explaining his executive action on immigration. President Reagan used his presidential authority for prosecutorial discretion (well he IS a saint or maybe a demigod to the Republican Party). But clearly, when President Obama does the same thing it is absolutely unconstitutional and he is acting like an emperor—or so say Republican congressional leaders and presidential hopefuls. We are not off to a good start here.</p>
<p>Next, my message to the Democrats—again.</p>
