rm elections because politicians everywhere can learn from the most masterful campaign announcement I have seen in ages. Now to be clear, as a Democrat I have been pleased with our prospects for a new Mayor ever since Frank Short first announced that he was running. The &#8230; <a href="http://indyvanguard.org/joe-hogsett-announced-for-mayor-a-textbook-start-to-his-campaign/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:10:"Len Farber";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2929:"<div class="pf-content"><p>I am intercalating a post on local politics between my reflections on the mid-term elections because politicians everywhere can learn from the most masterful campaign announcement I have seen in ages. Now to be clear, as a Democrat I have been pleased with our prospects for a new Mayor ever since Frank Short first announced that he was running. The addition of Ed DeLaney showed that Indianapolis Democrats have more than one good candidate to choose from and we all were expecting this move by Joe Hogsett. While I may have my preferences which I will keep to myself for a while longer, I can honestly state that I would happily support either Ed DeLaney or Joe Hogsett next November (Frank Short dropped out in favor of Joe Hogsett).</p>
<p>Last Wednesday, on a rather cold night, Joe Hogsett made his official announcement to a reasonably sized crowd outdoors at the Landmark for Peace Memorial in Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. Park. The symbolism of the location was not missed by any of the speakers, nor by your blogger whose first visit to Indianapolis involved bringing a group of students down from Michigan to work for Bobby Kennedy in the Indiana Presidential Primary.</p>
<p>This was only the beginning. Joe Hogsett pulled out all of the stops. The first speaker of the evening was City-County Council President Maggie Lewis. After some preliminary remarks, she introduced Bill Crawford, one of the doyens of the African American community in the Democratic Party. Having shown strong support from that portion of the Democratic coalition, retired Representative Crawford introduced the heart of the old guard, former Governor and former Senator Evan Bayh. It was Evan Bayh&#8217;s job to finally introduce Joe Hogsett.</p>
<p>Joe&#8217;s speech covered all of the bases as well. He began with the highly relevant and ever popular staple, crime. He advocated Community Policing as part of the answer and then moved on to talk about education (including pre-school) as well as discussing neighborhoods, sidewalks, and support for small business. He talked about fiscal responsibility, which can sound like a Republican idea—or a rebuke of Mayor Ballard&#8217;s brand of crony capitalism. In short, there was something for everyone in his speech, from the bluest of Blue Dogs to the Progressive wing of the Party.</p>
<p>The gathering afterward was at the iconic Kountry Kitchen, a place of such significance in the community that candidate Obama felt compelled to visit there in 2008. All in all, this was a tour de force of a campaign beginning. While I don&#8217;t think Ed DeLaney, a great campaigner in his own right, will be scared off by this, it almost looked like Joe Hogsett was saying, “Folks, I have this one sewed up.” I can foresee one thing for certain, whether or not there is a contested Democratic primary, the general campaign promises to be a vigorous one.</p>
