		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:35:"Midterm Election 2014: A Postmortem";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:59:"http://indyvanguard.org/midterm-election-2014-a-postmortem/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:68:"http://indyvanguard.org/midterm-election-2014-a-postmortem/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Fri, 07 Nov 2014 02:52:58 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:2:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Thoughts";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:21:"2014 General Election";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"http://indyvanguard.org/?p=1719";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:467:"Two days after the 2014 midterm election—the sun rose again today. For Democrats, this isn’t a happy time, but let’s get this one over. OK, the Democrats got whomped—big time. There, I said it. Let’s look at this from all sides and see if we can gain some perspective. First, is there a real message here and if so, what &#8230; <a href="http://indyvanguard.org/midterm-election-2014-a-postmortem/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:10:"Len Farber";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5600:"<div class="pf-content"><p>Two days after the 2014 midterm election—the sun rose again today. For Democrats, this isn’t a happy time, but let’s get this one over. OK, the Democrats got whomped—big time. There, I said it.</p>
<p>Let’s look at this from all sides and see if we can gain some perspective. First, is there a real message here and if so, what is it? It is easy for the Republicans to crow that the electorate has rejected “liberal Democrats” and have embraced “conservative” values. They are entitled to crow, but that isn’t what happened. Part of this was the typical difference between the “midterm electorate” and the “presidential-year electorate”. More Republican voters are consistent in their voting, while Democratic voters are less consistent—only voting in years with Presidential elections.  But to brush this off with that fact would be to miss the big picture. The Republicans did a lot right and the Democrats did a lot wrong. There was also a message from the middle. This was not a message about embracing the Republicans, nor was it a message about rejecting the Democrats. This was a Primal Scream from the middle. They are very unhappy, worried about the future and seeing a very scary present. They want something different—anything different, and the Republicans had the better sales pitch.</p>
<p>The Republicans did things right. Let’s admit that. They selected a group of likeable, reliable candidates, they backed off on social issues, and in fact they zeroed in on a single issue: Obama. In that, they were very successful. They have spent the past six years repeating over and over how Obama is an evil dictatorial, socialist, communist, Nazi, Muslim, foreigner. They don’t have to point out that he is also Black. The underlying racism is there for the Republicans to add to their votes, which is to say they have attracted and energized racists along with their non-racist base. They were also whipping up fear—fear over ISIS and fear over Ebola. I witnessed the clearest example of this anti-Obama sentiment on Election Day when a voter told me that she liked the Democratic candidate for State Representative, but couldn’t vote for her because a vote for any Democrat was a vote for Obama and he was destroying the country. I am still unclear on how the country is being destroyed, but I know she was certain that it is being destroyed. The Republicans stayed on message and won.</p>
<p>The Democrats have done many things wrong leading up to this election, but some of it is a long-term problem. The Democrats were scared to death by Ronald Reagan’s popula and Teflon-coating. They have never recovered. “Liberal? Me? No way, I spit on Liberals! No, I am not Obama! No, I don’t like Obamacare, no matter how many people it helps.” Strategically, the Democrats are so frightened that they can’t see where their strengths are. Look at how many minimum-wage ballot initiatives won, but did the Democrats embrace a pro-minimum wage message? Did they pound the Republicans on it? No, they didn’t. Did they point out how much Obamacare helped people in places like Kentucky where people have signed up in large numbers? No, they ran from that too. It is not a winning strategy to say “I am not Obama” when there is a Republican alternative that clearly isn’t Obama. Additionally, the Obama administration and his political team have been making mistakes as well. Obama has spent his first six years mostly trying to appease his critics (who will always dislike him) and ignoring the people who elected him. To be sure, his legacy as the President who finally did something about healthcare is fixed in history, but on LGBT issues he came late. On immigration, he became the “strict enforcer” and border closer with the promise of some relief for the Dreamers later. He delayed acting on immigration in any way before the election. The results show in decreased support and decreased enthusiasm within the Latino community. He also hurt the Democrats with his desire to hold onto his supporters turning his political army into a bunch a rally-holding, petition-signing, apolitical people. The younger voters remained uninspired.</p>
<p>I should also point out that the more progressive elements in the electorate either aren’t strategic thinkers, or they just haven’t been built into a real coalition. So let me startle a few people and state here that I was for HJR6/HJR3. Why? It is simple. The Republicans knew how to use anti-LGBT ballot initiatives to turn out their voters. The Democrats should have done the same. If an anti-same sex marriage proposal was on the ballot, it would have brought out a lot of voters who would have been outraged by the idea. Instead, it died quietly in the legislature and those people stayed home. If some of you are worried that it might have succeeded, understand this. True equality is not based on a vote in some election. It will come when the Supreme Court finally states: Look you idiots! This is a basic human right, one of the inalienable rights our Founding Fathers wrote about! You don’t get to vote on it!</p>
<p>I will have more to say about the meaning of this election for the future, but for now it is simple. The Republicans ran a great, policy-free, anti-Obama campaign and the Democrats ran poor campaigns. There were exceptions, like here in Marion County where the Democrats know how to do it. For the Democrats I can say “Kudos, Marion County Democrats.” You did well and we will have to be satisfied with that for now.</p>
</div>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:64:"http://indyvanguard.org/midterm-election-2014-a-postmortem/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:4;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:51:"
		
		
		
		
		
				
		
		
		

		
		
				
			
		
