0; <a href="http://indyvanguard.org/ebola-aids-and-bad-public-policy/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:10:"Len Farber";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4990:"<div class="pf-content"><p>Yesterday, I <a href="http://indyvanguard.org/jonas-salk-a-personal-memory/">posted about the Centennial of Jonas Salk’s birth</a>. As I mentioned, during my early years, polio was a very real and very scary disease. After Dr. Salk (and Dr. Albert Sabin), it has been fading into memory. When I met Dr. Salk, AIDS was the new scary disease. In America we tended to view it as a “gay disease” with the occasional hemophiliac thrown in, but the fear was huge. At that time, little was known about AIDS. HIV, the cause of AIDS, was known to be a “latent virus”, meaning that it took a long time to develop the disease after you caught the virus. It was believed that everyone who got infected with HIV would eventually get the disease and that those who got the disease would die, as there was no cure and, at that time, no one had been known to survive.</p>
<p>Even though it was a “gay disease”, fear was rampant. In 1987, the Ray family lived in the town of Arcadia, Florida. Three children in the family suffered from Hemophilia and all three got infected with the HIV virus during blood transfusions to treat their Hemophilia. A fearful local school board banned the children from attending the public school. The Ray family sued and won in court, so their good neighbors proceeded to burn their house down. They moved to Sarasota.</p>
<p>I will point out that there was no official outpouring of support for the Ray family, but President Reagan felt compelled to call the McClure family in Midland, Texas after their daughter, Baby Jessica, fell into a well in their back yard and was trapped for over two days.</p>
<p>Around this time, Luc Montagnier, the ‘co-discoverer’ of the HIV virus was invited to give a talk at our institute, Scripps Clinic and Research Institute. AIDS discussions abounded before the talk and there were also suggestions of massive quarantines for anyone exposed to the virus (or thought to have been exposed). One proponent of quarantine (or at least he was open to the idea) was my friend Chris. I must admit that he has one of the finest minds I have ever come across. He has an MD and a PhD and was finishing his double Residency in neurology and psychiatry. His research was in the then-brand-new field of magnetoencephalography, a sophisticated, non-invasive method of brain imaging.</p>
<p>I pointed out that even given the little that we knew, there were some basic principles of biology that would lead us to a number of conclusions. One of the simplest ones was that HIV must not be very contagious. Among the families of hemophiliacs that had contracted HIV through blood transfusions, not a single case of HIV infection had been reported. Time has proven my predictions correct, but Chris, being a real scientist, accepted the evidence then and there, conceding that quarantine was not a worthwhile idea.</p>
<p>And this brings us to today where the fear of Ebola is fueling fear in many quarters. Seal the country! Quarantine everyone who has been in West Africa! Stop people from entering the country from Central America (Okay, some politicians have a poor sense of geography)! New Jersey Governor Christie and New York Governor Cuomo, among others, joined the quarantine bandwagon. Kaci Hickox, a nurse who returned from volunteer work helping to treat Ebola patients in Sierra Leone, was forcibly quarantined upon her return. While she has been released (after much bad publicity about this) and the Governors have backed down a little, the fear mongering and pandering by politicians continues.</p>
<p>While Dr. Anthony Fauci, director of the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Disease (NIAID), recently suggested on The Diane Rehm Show, that all of the calls for quarantines by politicians were honest attempts to do the right thing out of concern for our citizens, I am not certain I want to be so quick to ascribe virtuous motives. Given the rampant anti-science rhetoric that comes from some of these same politicians and their love for being seen as ‘tough and resolute’, it looks to me very much like fear-mongering, pandering to our basest instincts, and jockeying for position before election day this year and in 2016. The science is clear on Ebola as well. It is very hard to catch and people without symptoms of illness are not infectious.  Sorry, Rand Paul.</p>
<p>We need to let medical science direct our policy in these areas. We generally don’t tell our auto mechanics or plumbers how to do their jobs and we shouldn’t try to tell medical scientists either. Pragmatism is the truly American school of philosophy. &#8220;Does it work? Prove it!&#8221; Well, evidence is the basis of medical science and evidence-based policies would serve our country best. Neither citizens nor politicians should be making our decisions based upon what seems popular at the time. As Jack Webb’s character Joe Friday used to say: &#8220;Just the facts ma’am.&#8221;</p>
</div>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:62:"http://indyvanguard.org/ebola-aids-and-bad-public-policy/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:5;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:48:"
		
		
		
		
		
				
		
		

		
		
				
			
		
