span></a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:10:"Len Farber";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2780:"<div class="pf-content"><p>Tuesday would have been the 100<sup>th</sup> birthday of Dr. Jonas Salk.</p>
<p>I am of that age when I can remember pictures of iron lungs as news, not history, and polio was a real threat that was tamed while I was beginning elementary school.  Jonas Salk was a national hero and an inspiration for countless young people who would seek careers in science. I was one of them.</p>
<p>I met Dr. Salk at the institute that bears his name in La Jolla, California. Several top scientists were scheduled to give talks that afternoon, so we drove the short distance down to the Salk Institute to attend. My friend Doug and I were both post-doctoral fellows working at what is now the Scripps Research Institute. For those of you unfamiliar with this position, post-doctoral fellows are one step up on graduate students in the cheap labor of academic science. We typically worked 80-hour weeks for low pay, but this was our apprenticeship that might lead to a more permanent university position. It can actually be a fun stage in one’s life.</p>
<p>Doug and I moved to find seats and ended up some 15 or 20 rows back, several seats from the aisle. Then Dr. Salk followed us in and proceeded to take a seat next to Doug with whom he proceeded to chat for the duration of the talks. From everything I had been told by other friends who worked at the Salk Institute, this was typical Jonas Salk. He was unassuming and would often chat with junior staff.</p>
<p>Humility was one aspect I remember. There are two other points I want to make about Dr. Jonas Salk that are relevant in their contrast to today’s political culture. Jonas Salk was the product of PUBLIC EDUCATION and FREE public education at that. He attended public schools in New York and then went to City College of New York. City College was known for a couple of important things during those days. While admission was highly competitive, it did not discriminate against Jews and other minorities as other colleges did then. It also had free tuition. One other thing that distinguishes City College in retrospect is the large number of Nobel Prize winners and PhD recipients that it produced, including four from the class of 1937 alone. Imagine that—free public education producing the next generation of scientific leaders.</p>
<p>The other notable point about Dr. Salk is that although he had a very comfortable life, and an entire research institute to direct, he passed up the fortune he could have made had he just patented the Salk Vaccine. He didn’t; he believed that it should belong to the world. Can you imagine anyone doing that today?</p>
<p>Tomorrow’s post will bring up another memory from that time, this one relevant to the current Ebola crisis. Check back.</p>
</div>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:58:"http://indyvanguard.org/jonas-salk-a-personal-memory/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:6;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:54:"
		
		
		
		
		
				
		
		
		
		

		
		
				
			
		
		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:30:"2014 Marion County Voter Guide";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:55:"http://indyvanguard.org/2014-marion-county-voter-guide/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:64:"http://indyvanguard.org/2014-marion-county-voter-guide/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Sat, 04 Oct 2014 03:57:26 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:5:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Thoughts";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:21:"2014 General Election";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:12:"Early Voting";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:18:"Voter Registration";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:14:"Voting by Mail";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"http://indyvanguard.org/?p=1711";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:507:"The 2014 Indiana General Election is rapidly approaching.  Hopefully this post will provide the information that citizens of Marion County need to exercise their right to vote.  There are many state and county offices up for election.  Most importantly, the deadline to register to vote in Indiana is noon on Monday, October 6.  Therefore, if you are reading this before &#8230; <a href="http://indyvanguard.org/2014-marion-county-voter-guide/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16:"Bryan Lilienkamp";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8294:"<div class="pf-content"><p>The 2014 Indiana General Election is rapidly approaching.  Hopefully this post will provide the information that citizens of Marion County need to exercise their right to vote.  There are many state and county offices up for election.  Most importantly, the deadline to register to vote in Indiana is <strong>noon on Monday, October 6</strong>.  Therefore, if you are reading this before that time, and are not registered to vote in Indiana:</p>
<p><strong>Register to vote!</strong></p>
<p>To register to vote in the Indiana General Election you must do so by <strong>noon, Monday, October 6, 2014</strong>.  The easiest way to register at this point would be to do so online at the <a href="https://indianavoters.in.gov/PublicSite/PublicMain.aspx" target="_blank">Indiana Statewide Voter Registration System website</a> .  On this page you can register to vote for the first time, confirm your current registration, make necessary name or address changes to your voter registration, find your Nov. 4 polling location, and find the candidates that will be on your ballot.  <strong>After noon on October 6</strong> voter registration in Indiana will be <strong>closed</strong> for this November’s election.</p>
<p>To register to vote in Indiana you must be a citizen of the United States, <strong>18 years old on November 4, 2014</strong>, reside at the address you are registering from, and not currently be in prison.  You must possess a current and valid Indiana driver&#8217;s license or Indiana identification card for non-drivers to register online.  If you don’t have this you should register to vote in person at the appropriate county voter registration office(in Marion County this is the first floor of the City-County building) before noon on Monday, October 6.</p>
<p><strong>Important note:  Felons are not prohibited from voting in Indiana.  College students attending school in Indiana from other states are not prohibited from voting in Indiana.</strong></p>
<p><strong>Offices on the 2014 General Election Ballot</strong></p>
<p>The following offices will be on the ballot:</p>
<p><strong>Statewide:</strong>  Indiana Secretary of State, State Auditor, and State Treasurer</p>
<p><strong>Federal:  </strong>every United States Representative</p>
<p><strong>Indiana State Senate:  </strong>half of the members of the Indiana State Senate</p>
<p><strong>Indiana House of Representatives: </strong> every Indiana State Representative</p>
<p><strong>Marion County:  </strong>Circuit Court Judge, Prosecutor, Clerk, Auditor, Recorder, Sheriff, Assessor, and Superior Court Judges</p>
<p><strong>Marion County Townships: </strong>Trustee, Small Claims Court Judge, and Constable</p>
<p>There are also Retention questions for Indiana Supreme Court and other Judges.</p>
<p>There are also School Board offices on the ballot.</p>
<p><strong>Absentee Voting by Mail</strong></p>
<p>You may vote by mail in Indiana by first submitting an <a href="http://www.in.gov/sos/elections/files/ABS-MAIL_(2014).pdf" target="_blank">Application for Absentee Ballot by Mail</a> .  The deadline to submit your application to vote by mail for the 2014 General Election is <strong>11:59PM, Monday, October 27, 2014</strong>.  There is also a <a href="http://www.in.gov/sos/elections/2402.htm" target="_blank">Spanish version of this application</a> available for download.  <strong>Voter ID is not needed to vote by mail.</strong>  To be eligible to vote by mail in Indiana one of the following must apply to you:</p>
<ul>
<ol>
<li>You have a specific, reasonable expectation that you will be absent from the county on Election Day during the entire 12 hours that the polls are open (6 am until 6 pm).</li>
<li>You have a disability.</li>
<li>You are at least 65 years of age.</li>
<li>You will have official election duties outside of your voting precinct.</li>
<li>You are scheduled to work at your regular place of employment during the entire 12 hours that the polls are open.</li>
<li>You will be confined due to illness or injury or you will be caring for an individual confined due to illness or injury during the entire 12 hours that the polls are open.</li>
<li>You are prevented from voting because of a religious discipline or religious holiday during the entire 12 hours that the polls are open.</li>
<li>You are a participant in the state&#8217;s address confidentiality program.</li>
<li>You are a member of the military or a public safety officer.</li>
</ol>
</ul>
<p>After you receive your mail-in ballot, the deadline to mail, fax, or hand-deliver your completed absentee ballot is noon on Election Day, Tuesday, November 4, 2014.  Complete information about voting by mail can be found at <a href="http://www.indy.gov/eGov/County/Clerk/Election/Voter_Info/beforeed/Pages/Mail.aspx" target="_blank">this page on the Marion County Clerk’s website</a> .</p>
<p><strong>Important!  If you change your mind and decide to vote in person on Election Day after sending in your absentee ballot application, you must bring the absentee ballot you received in the mail to the precinct inspector at your polling location in order to have it voided before you are allowed to vote in person.  Otherwise you will have to vote a provisional ballot.</strong></p>
<p><strong>Voting Early In-Person at the City-County Building</strong></p>
<p>Marion County registered voters may also vote early in-person <strong>only</strong> at the City-County Building at 200 E. Washington St., Room W122.  Voters are advised to enter the building from the <strong>Delaware Street entrance</strong>.  The schedule for voting early in-person is:</p>
<p>Tuesday, October 7 to Friday, October 10, 8AM to 5PM<br />
Monday, October 13 to Friday, October 17, 8AM to 5PM<br />
Monday, October 20 to Friday, October 24, 8AM to 5PM<br />
Saturday, October 25 &amp; Sunday, October 26, 10AM to 5PM<br />
Monday, October 27 to Friday, October 31, 8AM to 8PM<br />
Saturday, November 1 &amp; Sunday, November 2 – 10AM to 5PM<br />
<strong>Last day! </strong>Monday, November 3 – 8AM to 12PM (noon)</p>
<p>Voters will be <strong>required</strong> to provide voter ID to vote early in-person in exactly the same way as is required to vote in their precinct on Election Day.  <strong>Any Marion County registered voter may vote early in-person.</strong></p>
<p><strong>Voting in Marion County on Election Day, November 4</strong></p>
<p>If you don’t exercise the above options you will need to vote in your precinct on November 4, 2014.  The polls will be open from 6 a.m. to 6 p.m., and voter ID will be <strong>required</strong> in order to vote.  An excellent source of information regarding your polling location, voting districts, current elected officials, candidates, and sample ballots is the <a href="http://maps.indy.gov/VIP/" target="_blank">Voter Information Portal</a> on the Marion County Clerk’s website.</p>
<p><strong>Voter ID for Both the November Election Day and Early Voting In-Person</strong></p>
<p>Acceptable voter ID in Indiana must:</p>
<ol>
<li>Display your photo.</li>
<li>Display your name, and the name must conform to your voter registration record. Conform does not mean identical.</li>
<li>Display an expiration date and either be current or have expired sometime after the date of the last General Election, meaning after November 6, 2012.</li>
<li>Be issued by the State of Indiana or the U.S. government.</li>
</ol>
<p>In most cases, an Indiana driver license, Indiana photo ID card, Military ID or U.S. Passport is sufficient.  Complete rules can be found on the <a href="http://www.in.gov/sos/elections/2401.htm" target="_blank">Photo ID Law page</a> at the Indiana Secretary of State’s website.</p>
<p><strong>Additionally</strong>, many poll workers will be needed to work the polls on Election Day, November 4.  Complete information on this can be found on <a href="http://www.indy.gov/eGov/County/Clerk/Election/Workers_Info/Pages/default.aspx" target="_blank">this page on the Marion County Clerk’s website</a> .</p>
<p>Finally, the author wishes to express that this post is simply a guide to the voting rules in Marion County, Indiana and not an endorsement of these rules.  Thank you for voting!</p>
</div>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:60:"http://indyvanguard.org/2014-marion-county-voter-guide/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"3";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:7;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:51:"
		
		
		
		
		
				
		
		
		

		
		
				
			
		
		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:53:"Pence Plays Shell Game with Domestic Violence Funding";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:78:"http://indyvanguard.org/pence-plays-shell-game-with-domestic-violence-funding/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:87:"http://indyvanguard.org/pence-plays-shell-game-with-domestic-violence-funding/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Fri, 26 Sep 2014 01:18:43 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:4:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Thoughts";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:14:"Governor Pence";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Indiana Domestic Violence Plans";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:14:"Indy Feminists";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"http://indyvanguard.org/?p=1704";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:552:"Since Indiana’s Governor Pence repeatedly highlights his pro-life beliefs and priority to the family unit, it’s understandable his 12 appointees to the Indiana Criminal Justice Institute (ICJI) would be addressing the rise in domestic violence along with the rest of the country. Calls to shelters in Indiana have increased dramatically: one shelter has turned away 79 individuals in the past &#8230; <a href="http://indyvanguard.org/pence-plays-shell-game-with-domestic-violence-funding/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:12:"Marie Siroky";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3840:"<div class="pf-content"><p>Since Indiana’s Governor Pence repeatedly highlights his pro-life beliefs and priority to the family unit, it’s understandable his 12 appointees to the Indiana Criminal Justice Institute (ICJI) would be addressing the rise in domestic violence along with the rest of the country. Calls to shelters in Indiana have increased dramatically: one shelter has turned away 79 individuals in the past three months. In 2013, 58 people were murdered in Domestic Violence incidents; various Indiana DV agencies and over 60,000 called crisis lines served over 30,000 individuals.</p>
<p>So Monday morning’s tweet by Governor Pence was taken as good news by most media and the rest of the world:</p>
<p><a href="http://indyvanguard.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Pence-quote09222014.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1705" src="http://indyvanguard.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Pence-quote09222014.jpg" alt="Pence quote09222014" width="580" height="388" /></a></p>
<p>Except it’s all spin… or bull. And media outlets are headlining this “extra” funding.</p>
<p>Yet as posted by Indy Feminists:<a href="http://indyvanguard.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Indy-Feminists-quote.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1706" src="http://indyvanguard.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Indy-Feminists-quote.jpg" alt="Indy Feminists quote" width="580" height="258" /></a></p>
<p>The catalyst came last week when the ICJI announced they were withholding $1.2 million of the amount approved by the General Assembly for Domestic Violence programs.  David Hall of the ICJI wants more “appropriate reporting”.  Advocates were outraged and Pence announced via twitter that he wasn’t withholding funds.</p>
<p>Not accurate. In fact, the State already took back over $300,000 approved for programs from last year to save money. Yes—the same year when over 600 people were turned away from residential shelters due to no room. Fiscal conservative, pro-family Pence saved some money by taking it away from domestic violence victims and their families. Appropriate reporting would entail revealing why that money was taken back. To date the ICJI has no answer and is looking in to it.</p>
<p>Also, the ICJI’s claim that the submitted budget from DV agencies isn’t adequate is insulting.  Many of these agencies received grant funding using the same budgets that have been scrutinized and approved by the state and the grantors. What else is needed?</p>
<p>Looking at Domestic Violence – it is driven by misplacement of emotions – power, fear, anger, etc. Politics also invokes this misuse of emotions. Victims hear the words of support and promises from the Governor and his appointed board, but actions speak louder and slam doors in their faces. So Pence’s promise of new money pouring in sounds good.  But this promise is as insidious as the ones perpetrators give when rationalizing their actions; Pence has managed to shift the focus back to him.</p>
<p>Truth is there are no added funds or new money immediately available. The  $740,426 of “additional” funds includes the $344,000 never allocated last year and mysteriously returned, along with another $448,000 of already allocated funding.</p>
<p>The General Assembly approved the $4.2 million, which is an increase to match a need. Then the ICJI board (comprised of mostly Pence appointees) decides not to release the funds. Then the Governor overrules them and wants the money expedited.  And they give back the reverted funds without an explanation as to why it was taken away to begin with.</p>
<p>So in essence, the Governor is letting the General Assembly do their job, minus the input of a board of his appointees.  But he wants the credit.</p>
<p>And that is nothing new&#8211;just like this “new” money.</p>
