org/the-marriage-equality-train-is-picking-up-speed/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:13:"Annette Gross";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:7383:"<div class="pf-content"><p>Last week at our Indianapolis PFLAG meeting, our guest speaker, attorney Steve Fulk, shared some of the history of the LGBT movement in the United States. Relatively speaking, this is a fairly new movement.  We know that gay people have existed since time began; however, Steve marks the Stonewall Rising as the beginning of the “movement” in our country.</p>
<p>Even when you look at the strides that have occurred since 1968, the past year has seen an incredible amount of movement—especially right here in our own backyard.  Last year at this time, thousands of Hoosiers—LGBT and straight allies—were joining the Freedom Indiana team to try to stop our state government from (once again) trying to enshrine discrimination into our state constitution. Phone calls were made to our fellow Hoosiers, letters and postcards were written to state legislators, and many of us met with those same state legislators.</p>
<p>All of this culminated in six hearings at the Statehouse—three in in the House and three in the Senate.  Those in support of Marriage Equality spent so many hours at the Statehouse dressed in red—the color of love—and heard hours of testimony, some of which was extremely insulting and disrespectful to our LGBT friends and loved ones.  After sitting in the House gallery at the first hearing, I chose to stand in the hallways for the rest of the hearings so I could express my reactions to what I heard inside the House and Senate chambers; one of my friends actually was asked to leave the gallery when he gave a thumbs-down to some of the testimony he didn’t approve of.</p>
<p>At the end of the day, we were successful in keeping HJR-3 at bay.  We were able to keep this odious bill from being voted on by our fellow Hoosiers.  In the meantime, 13 couples had filed suit against the state, requesting that their out-of-state marriages be recognized by their home state.  Four couples were represented by Indiana Equality Action; four couples were represented by the Indiana branch of the ACLU; and five couples were represented by Lambda Legal.</p>
<p>On June 25, 2014, U.S. District Court Judge Richard L. Young struck down Indiana’s law which bans same-sex marriage.  I heard the news from a fellow PFLAG member, and immediately rushed down to the Marion County Clerk’s office, where Clerk Beth White was issuing marriage licenses as fast as she could.  The line of people waiting to receive licenses was snaking out the door!  Until a stay was issued three days later, nearly 600 marriage licenses were issued in Marion County alone.</p>
<p>Not surprisingly, Governor Pence issued a memo to all executive branches, stating that Indiana’s law against same-sex marriages “is in full force and effect and executive branch agencies are to execute their functions as though the U.S. District Court order of June 25 had not been issued.”</p>
<p>Despite the fact that so many same-sex couples, along with their families and friends, were celebrating, on June 25<sup>th</sup> the U.S. Court of Appeals for the 7<sup>th</sup> Circuit issued a stay.  This really muddied the waters.  Were the recent marriages still legal or were these couples in limbo?</p>
<p>The next chapter saw the plaintiffs and their attorneys, along with Marriage Equality supporters in Chicago, where Judge Richard J. Posner, Judge Ann Claire Williams, and Judge David Hamilton heard testimony from attorneys in Indiana and Wisconsin who supported their states’ bans of same-sex marriage, as well as the attorneys for the plaintiffs.</p>
<p>I listened to the testimony on-line and could not believe some of the arguments that each state offered in support of their same-sex marriage bans. Judge Posner, who is a Reagan appointee and quite conservative, was easily able to strip away the state attorney’s arguments and reduce them to what I saw as nonsense.</p>
<p>On September 4<sup>th</sup>, nine days after the oral hearings, in a lightning-quick decision, the three-panel judge ruled that Indiana’s ban on same-sex marriage was unconstitutional.  In his opinion Judge Posner described the gay and lesbian community as among the most “misunderstood and discriminated-against minorities in the history of the world,” and that the denial of their right to marry has been a source of “continuing pain.”</p>
<p>In this merry-go-round of on-again, off-again marriages, Hoosier same-sex couples, along with their friends and families, celebrated once again. However, the stay remains in effect. Still in marriage-limbo, Hoosier same-sex couples found themselves awaiting a decision by the U.S. Supreme Court.</p>
<p>Once more, good news came quickly.  This week we learned that the U.S. Supreme Court listed gay marriage petitions from five states – including Indiana &#8211; for consideration at its Sept. 29 private conference.  Officials in those states are asking the court to decide whether their state bans on same-sex marriage are constitutional.</p>
<p>Five states have filed petitions:  Indiana, Oklahoma, Utah, Virginia and Wisconsin. There are now seven petitions for writ of certiorari pending. It remains to be seen whether the justices will take up any of the cases. Paul Castillo, staff attorney for Lambda Legal, said, “Only the highest court in the country can provide the secure relief that same-sex couples and their children need, and it’s extremely important that these families are able to count on the protections of marriage as soon as possible.&#8221;</p>
<p>Interestingly, marriage equality advocates are waiting to hear the outcome of oral arguments held last month in the 6<sup>th</sup> Circuit Court of Appeals, which heard arguments in cases from Kentucky, Michigan, Ohio, and Tennessee.  Some court watchers believe that the 6<sup>th</sup> Circuit could split from other courts and uphold those states’ same-sex marriage bans. From what I have learned, this is not as bad as it may seem. When two different circuit courts disagree on the constitutionality of a law, it is called a “circuit split.” And very often, the Supreme Court will intervene, and thus possibly speed up the process.</p>
<p>Now I do need to explain that it’s easy for me to say that things have moved quickly—I am not a part of any of the same-sex married couples whose lives are hanging in limbo. I am sure that they must feel that this has been dragging on way too long. My heart goes out to all of these couples. But I also applaud the plaintiffs who have stepped forward so that we can challenge this discriminatory law and move equality forward.</p>
<p>I am not a legal scholar, but I do have a good feeling about the ultimate outcome of these cases. The ideal scenario for Hoosier same-sex couples would be for our governor and Attorney General to stop wasting taxpayers’ money in defense of this discriminatory law. But I have no illusions that they will do that, that they will do the right thing. So we must wait and see if the Supreme Court decides to pick up any of the cases recently filed. And while we wait, the one thing we can do—we must do—is elect public officials who support equality and respect their LGBT constituents. That way we can ensure that future generations won’t have to spend their lives fighting for what should be theirs in the first place.</p>
</div>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:77:"http://indyvanguard.org/the-marriage-equality-train-is-picking-up-speed/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:9;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:51:"
		
		
		
		
		
				
		
		
		

		
		
				
			
		
		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:60:"Senator Donnelly’s Support for Overturning Citizens United";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:84:"http://indyvanguard.org/senator-donnellys-support-for-overturning-citizens-united-2/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:93:"http://indyvanguard.org/senator-donnellys-support-for-overturning-citizens-united-2/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Sat, 30 Aug 2014 15:43:11 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:4:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Thoughts";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:15:"Citizens United";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:14:"Public Citizen";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16:"Senator Donnelly";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"http://indyvanguard.org/?p=1698";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:503:"Every generation of Americans has amended the Constitution, and the proposed Democracy For All Amendment – which gets big money out of our political system – could be our generation’s legacy. It comes up for a vote in the U.S. Senate next Monday, but U.S. Sen. Joe Donnelly has yet to add his name as a co-sponsor. That’s why we’ll &#8230; <a href="http://indyvanguard.org/senator-donnellys-support-for-overturning-citizens-united-2/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:12:"Marc Barnett";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3961:"<div class="pf-content"><p>Every generation of Americans has amended the Constitution, and the proposed Democracy For All Amendment – which gets big money out of our political system – could be our generation’s legacy.</p>
<p>It comes up for a vote in the U.S. Senate next Monday, but U.S. Sen. Joe Donnelly has yet to add his name as a co-sponsor. That’s why we’ll be going to his office on Wednesday to urge him to sign on. We invite you to join us.</p>
<p>From the abolitionists to the women’s suffrage movement, the Constitution bears the marks of many generations who strived for a more democratic, equal nation. The Democracy For All Amendment could be this generation’s contribution to the advancement and perseverance of the principles of democracy for future generations.</p>
<p>The link between unlimited spending in politics – as established through the U.S. Supreme Court’s 2010 ruling in Citizens United v. Federal Election Commission <em>(FEC)</em> and this year’s <em>McCutcheon v. FEC</em> decision – and the limits on democracy is clear. The more money in politics, the more the will of the people is drowned out by the will of the wealthy few.</p>
<p>Democracy is supposed to be based on equality; however, there is nothing equal in the current system if <em>Citizens United </em>stands. That ruling gave corporations and the wealthy the green light to spend unlimited sums to influence elections. <em>Citizens United</em> transformed the electoral system, with elections costing billions of dollars, with much of it spent on attack ads.</p>
<p>Since <em>Citizens United</em>, the voice of the many is increasingly being drowned out. The current system caters to the interest of the rich donors, not the American people. The time to be heard is now; this is our generation’s chance, our generation’s issue, our generation’s amendment.</p>
<p>The majority of Americans stand with me and with you. Those that are aware of the <em>Citizens United </em>ruling are <a href="http://www.people-press.org/2012/01/17/super-pacs-having-negative-impact-say-voters-aware-of-citizens-united-ruling/" target="_blank">overwhelmingly in support</a> of some limits on election spending by corporations and the wealthy to limit their ability to manipulate the system. This issue transcends party affiliation, as polls show that the majority of Democrat and Republican voters believe that too much money is in politics.</p>
<p>The number of U.S. senators supporting the Democracy For All amendment sits at 5 <strong>Senator Donnelly has expressed support of the amendment; however, he has yet to co-sponsor it. His commitment to become the 51<sup>st</sup> senator to sign on would be monumental.</strong> He has a chance to make history and to be a profound voice in the effort to take our democracy back.</p>
<p>We, the people of Indiana, have a say. You can help urge Senator Donnelly to be a champion for democracy and for people. The vote in the Senate is Monday, September 8. It’s not too late to act and lobby for change. Make your voice heard.</p>
<p><strong>Please join your fellow democratic crusaders for a rally and petition delivery event at noon on Wednesday, Sept. 3, outside of Senator Donnelly’s Indianapolis office on 10 West Market St. There, we will deliver Indiana’s portion of the more than 3 million petitions signatures that have been gathered in support of an amendment</strong>.</p>
<p>You also can call Senator Donnelly’s office to register your support at 202-224-4814 (Washington D.C.) or 317-226-5555 (Indianapolis).</p>
<p>Our democracy has been threatened by the recent Supreme Court decisions. Support the Democracy For All amendment (S.J. Res. 19), and tell Senator Donnelly how you, the people of Indiana, feel about democracy.</p>
<p>Sincerely,</p>
<p>Marc Barnett</p>
<p><a href="http://www.citizen.org/" target="_blank">Public Citizen</a></p>
<p>Democracy Is For People Campaign</p>
